The symposium will include a series of concerts, a satellite workshop on Music Neurotechnology, and an unforgettable boat cruise and banquet trip around the iconic Plymouth Hoe from the Barbican Harbour, site of the Mayflower Steps (portrayed in the logo above), from which the Pilgrim Fathers left England [...]   </description>   <dc:date>2014-10-03T16:53:25+01:00</dc:date>   <dc:creator>Duncan Williams</dc:creator>   <dc:identifier>https://www.jiscmail.ac.uk:443/cgi-bin/webadmin?A2=HISTORY-OF-COMPUTING-UK;df689758.1410</dc:identifier> </item>  <item rdf:about="https://www.jiscmail.ac.uk:443/cgi-bin/webadmin?A2=HISTORY-OF-COMPUTING-UK;eebb15d6.1409">   <title>Fwd: Invitation: Privacy in the age of Edward Snowden </title>   <link>https://www.jiscmail.ac.uk:443/cgi-bin/webadmin?A2=HISTORY-OF-COMPUTING-UK;eebb15d6.1409</link>   <description> Dear computer historians,<br><br>This message may be of interest to those who are in and around London.<br><br>The University of Westminster is currently involved in the European<br>Union research project PACT (see http://www.projectpact.eu) that studies<br>privacy and security in Europe. Since Edward Snowden\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds revelations,<br>there have been a lot of discussions about privacy and surveillance in<br>Europe.
